Why is CLTV important:

In todays world growth of any business is driven by the amount of data a particular company possesses, through which effective decisions can be made to scale the business to greater heights. One such crucial strategies used by companies is to identify the customers who add more revenue to them in the long run. For example, bodybuilders and fitness freaks are primary consumers of meat and dairy products, they continuously invest in these products to reach their personal goals. This in turn poses as an advantage to meat and dairy industry to market their products better on different platforms to target their primary consumers. Retail sales can be maximized by just investing more resources on a meat shop located near a gym. Offers, discounts and other effective strategies can be applied by the business to generate more revenue and increase their profit. Hence, it becomes very crucial for a business to understand the value added by group of customers(who exhibit similar features) to grow their business. This is just an example of how customer lifetime value works with respect to a particular scenario. similar strategies can be applied by different industries.

What kind of a relation does CLV have with income?

  • Positive relationship.
  • People who have more income have higher CLV.
ggplot(data=data, aes(x= Income, y=Customer.Lifetime.Value, color = Education, fill=Education))+

Income and CLV relation for Education.

  • As the income of a masters student increases, their CLV has decreased.
  • Students of Masters and Bachelors whose income is high have low CLV.
  • Students of High School or Below, College, and Doctorate with high income have high CLV and low income has low CLV.

2.4 Location Code:

## which policy plan is more popular with respect to the location?
ggplot(data, aes(fill=Policy.Type, y=Customer.Lifetime.Value, x=Location.Code)) + 
  geom_bar(position="stack", stat="identity") +

  • It is observed that suburban areas generate more CLTV when compared to rural and urban areas and most of the CLTV comes predominantly from personal auto policy type, However Corporate auto is seen to generate higher CLTV in suburban areas compared to rural and urban areas. The company can invest more marketing resources like ads and agents for customers in suburban areas and concentrate on the second best policy type(corporate auto) rather than on the steadily increasing policy personal auto.

# data transformation:
df <-  data
## Binning income, Monthly Premium Auto, Months Since Last Claim
df$inc_range <- cut(df$`Income`, breaks = c(-1,0,20000,40000,60000, 80000, 100000), labels = c(0,1,2,3,4,5),ordered = TRUE)
df$pre_auto_range <- cut(df$`Monthly.Premium.Auto`,  breaks = seq(60, 300, by = 48), labels = c(0,1,2,3,4),ordered = TRUE)
df$mnt_lst_claim <- cut(df$`Months.Since.Last.Claim`, breaks = 6, labels = c(0,1,2,3,4,5),ordered = TRUE)

## Label encoding 
df$State = factor(df$State, level = c("Arizona","California","Nevada","Oregon","Washington"), 
 labels = c(1,2,3,4,5))
df$Gender = factor(df$Gender, level =c("F","M"), labels = c(1,2)) 
df$Marital.Status = factor(df$Marital.Status, level =c("Single","Married","Divorced"), labels = c(1,2,3))

df$Policy.Type = factor(df$Policy.Type, level =c("Corporate Auto","Personal Auto","Special Auto"),
 labels = c(1,2,3))

df$Response = factor(df$Response, level =c("No","Yes"), labels = c(0,1))

df$EmploymentStatus = factor(df$EmploymentStatus, level =c("Unemployed","Employed","Medical Leave",
 "Disabled","Retired"), labels = c(1,2,3,4,5))

df$Coverage = factor(df$Coverage, level = c("Basic","Extended","Premium"), labels = c(1,2,3))

df$Education = factor(df$Education, level =c("High School or Below","College","Bachelor","Master","Doctor"),
labels = c(1,2,3,4,5))

df$Location.Code = factor(df$Location.Code, level=c("Rural","Suburban","Urban"), labels = c(1,2,3))

df$Sales.Channel = factor(df$Sales.Channel, level =c("Agent","Branch","Call Center","Web"),
labels =c(1,2,3,4))

df$Vehicle.Size = factor(df$Vehicle.Size, level =c("Small","Medsize","Large"), labels = c(1,2,3))

df$Vehicle.Class = factor(df$Vehicle.Class, level =c("Two-Door Car","Four-Door Car","SUV","Sports Car",
 "Luxury Car", "Luxury SUV"), labels = c(1,2,3,4,5,6))

df$Renew.Offer.Type = factor(df$Renew.Offer.Type, level =c("Offer1", "Offer2","Offer3","Offer4"),

Conclusuion:

We build 2 models considering the customer lifetime value as the target variable. One is a regression approach, Linear regressor is used to predict the values of Customer Lifetime Value.

In most scenarios, companies are more concerned on finding the level of value a customer can offer to the company in the long run. For this purpose a KNN classifier was used to classify customer based on their lifetime value into four levels(1,2,3 and 4). 1 being the lowest and 4 being the highest). A given customer is categorized within these four categories which helps the company maintain a good relationship with the customers accordingly and scale their business in the long run.

We also tried using regression over the knn predicted cluster to find out the clv amount of particular customer. There was major limitation in the approach is that if by chance our predicted cluster goes wrong entire regression predicted amount for customer lifetime value will be misleading.
